vokes httpd_h2_serve_slot for HTTP/2 handlingthis step blocks reading the connection preface before ALPN is determined. The sequence in proxy_accept_batch is: 1. accept, 2. add client to epoll, 3. perform TLS handshake (should complete before HTTP/2), 4. proceed with HTTP/2 processing.When n1, no fork is needed; the server should run the epoll loop in the main process.\n\nThe issue may lie in SSL_accept during the handshake process. The flow involves epoll_wait, then a readable listen fd, followed by proxy_accept_batch which accepts and performs TLS handshake. The client should be added to epoll before the TLS handshake begins, ensuring that when SSL_accept reads from the fd, it works correctly. This ordering ensures proper handling of the TLS handshake within the epoll loop.\n\nSSL_accept might fail due to non-blocking socket behavior, with only 32 polling attempts of 5 seconds each, though that timeout seems sufficient.\n\nThe flow appears correct: proxy_accept_batch is called only when epoll_wait returns on the listen fd, and the server remains in epoll_wait during the TLS handshake.\n\nThe issue could be that OpenSSL connects successfully, but the server's epoll is not yet monitoring the listen socket. However, since the server is configured to listen per ss, this seems unlikely.\n\nTesting HTTP without TLS on the same configuration is not feasible, as the setup requires TLS.\n\nRunning strace on the SSL_accept path may reveal issues. Re-reading lib.li shows that proxy_handle_client_in is called only after TLS for HTTP/1.1, while httpd_h2_serve_slot is used for HTTP/2, which blocks in a read loop. When openssl s_client connects without sending an HTTP/2 preface immediately after the handshake, OpenSSL may complete the TLS handshake and wait. In this case:\n\n1. Accept and complete TLS handshake with openssl s_client.\n2. If ALPN selects http/1.1, proxy_handle_client_in is called.\n3. If ALPN selects h2, httpd_h2_serve_slot is called and waits for the preface.Whe