          "text": "No libssl-dev installed, and sudo installation is not possible.\n\nSince libssl-dev isn't available and sudo installation isn't possible, I need to explore alternative approaches. I could re-execute openssl s_server as a TLS terminator forwarding to plain HTTP, though that feels like cheating for \"runtime on li-httpd.\" Bundling a minimal TLS implementation would be too complex. A better option is to vendor just the necessary OpenSSL headers and link dynamically against libssl.so.3. I could copy headers from a known location or embed minimal declarations in li_rt_tls.c. For OpenSSL 3.x, I can use explicit function declarations via dlopen/dlsym without needing headers at compile time, or add minimal forward declarations like `typedef struct ssl_st SSL;`.\n\nThe standard approach without the dev package involves using `dlopen(\"libssl.so.3\")` and `dlsym` to load all required functions at runtime, eliminating the need for compile-time headers beyond `dlfcn.h`. \n\nI will implement `li_rt_tls.c` with dynamic OpenSSL loading via `dlopen`. This approach is suitable for optional TLS support.\n\nFunctions to be loaded dynamically:\n- `OPENSSL_init_ssl`\n- `TLS_server_method` or `TLS_method`\n- `SSL_CTX_new`, `SSL_CTX_use_certificate_file`, `SSL_CTX_use_PrivateKey_file`\n- `SSL_CTX_set_min_proto_version`, `SSL_CTX_set_alpn_select_cb` or `SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos`\n\nSSL_new, SSL_set_fd, SSL_accept, SSL_read, SSL_write, SSL_get0_alpn_selected, SSL_free, SSL_CTX_free, ERR_get_error, and ERR_error_string are the required OpenSSL functions to be loaded dynamically.\n\nFor HTTP/2, a minimal implementation without nghttp2 requires a frame parser in C.\n\nThe implementation plan includes:\n1. Creating `runtime/li_rt_tls.h` for the API\n2. Implementing `runtime/li_rt_tls.c` with dlopen for OpenSSL, TLS context initialization, accept, read/write operations\n3. Adding `runtime/li_rt_h2.h` and `runtime/li_rt_h2.c` for minimal HTTP/2 server or merging into li_rt_tls.